                        a: "You are not facing a performance problem; you are facing a 'Resilience Architecture' failure. The belief that high performance requires constant intensity is a dangerous and counterproductive myth. Sustainable high performance requires both intense work and intense recovery. You have architected for one but not the other.\n\nThe Sustainable Performance Protocol:\n• Define and Model Boundaries: Leaders must explicitly define and model sustainable work habits, such as taking real vacations and establishing communication blackouts during non-work hours. This gives the rest of the team permission to do the same.\n• Focus on Output, Not Hours: Shift performance evaluation to be based on the achievement of clear, pre-agreed goals (like OKRs), not on the number of hours worked or \"face time\".\n• Implement 'Recovery' Rituals: Intentionally create rituals that encourage recovery, such as company-wide \"recharge\" days after a major launch or \"no-meeting Fridays\" to allow for deep work.\n• Train Managers on Burnout Prevention: Train your managers to spot the early signs of burnout on their teams and give them the tools and autonomy to address it, such as adjusting workloads or encouraging time off.",
