                        a: "You are approaching a critical capital allocation decision without an architectural framework. The belief that M&A is purely opportunistic is a dangerous assumption. A reactive approach to M&A is a path to strategic distraction and value destruction.\n\nThe Strategic M&A Framework:\n• Define the Strategic Rationale: As a leadership team, define the 1-2 specific strategic gaps that an acquisition could fill (e.g., \"accelerate entry into a new market,\" \"acquire a key technology,\" \"buy a competitor\").\n• Develop a 'Buy vs. Build' Model: For each potential target, create a simple model that compares the cost and time of acquiring them versus building the same capability in-house. This forces an objective, data-driven decision.\n• Run a Disciplined Diligence Process: Appoint a single internal owner for the M&A process. Run a structured diligence process that evaluates not just the technology and financials, but also the critical, and often overlooked, element of cultural fit.\n• Create a 100-Day Integration Plan: Before the deal is signed, create a detailed 100-day integration plan with a dedicated owner. A failure to integrate is a failure of the acquisition.",
